b'Meet Pascal, a managing director in Private Wealth Management, who switched from being a professional athlete to banking and now works in our #Frankfurt office. #GSOutOfOffice 
 
\xe2\x80\x9cAs a native Swiss, winter sports are second nature to me. I found my passion in Nordic Combined and decided to turn it into a career. I competed professionally from 1996 to 2006 and even was a long-term member of the Swiss National and the 2006 Torino Winter Olympic team.
 
I decided to retire from being a professional athlete because I wanted to pursue something more than flying up to 200m with just skis on my feet and skating through snowy woods year after year. Furthermore, I didn\xe2\x80\x98t see a chance to make it into the top ranks of the world as a professional skier. I decided to strive for excellence in a completely different industry that I had been fascinated with for a very long time, so I joined wealth management in 2008. This was a wonderful decision - while enabling and inspiring people, coaching the team to its highest performance or acquiring new business for the firm, I feel exactly the same passion energizing me as I did during my sports career.
 
Besides simply drawing parallels between professional sports and business challenges, I still enjoy sports and being physically active. I do cross-country skiing in the winter as well as mountain biking, road bike riding and running in the summer. It is very important to me to be a good example for my two young children and also maintain the right balance between challenging days in the office and exercising in nature.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'For every $10.00 you spend on music, $3.80 goes to the labels, $3.30 to the platform, $1.70 to the artist, and $0.60 each to the publishers and songwriters. Does the music biz need a shake up? Increase your industry knowledge with our full Music In The Air infographic at the link in our bio.'

b'#WhatAreYouReading? James Wang, a managing director in our Hong Kong Investment Banking Division, recently picked up \xe2\x80\x9cMisbehaving: The Making of Behavioral Economics\xe2\x80\x9d by Richard H Thaler. For James, it was an important read as someone who works in finance: \xe2\x80\x9cThe book helps us understand the big role human psychology plays in the decision-making process, and thus the various anomalies created in the financial world. As a professional working in financial services, it is critical to understand clients and the market through psychologists\xe2\x80\x99 lenses, rather than simply relying on data analysis to conclude advice.\xe2\x80\x9d Let us know your recent reads in the comments.'

b'This morning marked our fifth annual #GSGives Analyst Impact Fund\xe2\x80\x94a global competition that gives analysts a chance to compete to win grants for nonprofits of their choice. We\xe2\x80\x99re proud to announce this year\xe2\x80\x99s winner: SIRUM, an organization that seeks to ensure that every American has access to their essential prescription medication. b'Creating a sense of normalcy right now might be challenging, but C\xc3\xa9line M\xc3\xa9chain, a partner in our Paris office, finds it paramount to staying clear-headed and productive. What\xe2\x80\x99s been the best part of your new routine?'

b'We led a $15 million funding round for @ZestMoney, a fintech startup that lends to millions of Indian consumers who lack access to traditional credit. Learn more via the link in our bio. #GSsustainability'

b'We worked with Ecuador to issue a $400 million social bond\xe2\x80\x94the first social bond issuance by a sovereign\xe2\x80\x94to support Casa Para Todos, a government program designed to build affordable housing. Learn more via the link in our bio. #GSsustainability'

b'Today, we take a moment to remember 9/11, and honor the brave and the fallen. #NeverForget #TributeInLight'

b'#WhatAreYouReading? As we celebrate #ReadABookDay, we\xe2\x80\x99re reflecting on Managing Director Masahiro Ehara\xe2\x80\x99s submission, \xe2\x80\x9cZeno and the Tortoise\xe2\x80\x94How to Think Like a Philosopher,\xe2\x80\x9d a book so impactful to Masahiro that it changed the way he walks into our Tokyo office every morning. He explains, \xe2\x80\x9cEach of us has more #influence over others than we might realize. It excited me to think that even a junior analyst can create a ripple of positive energy that fills a whole room or brightens up a teleconference. Ever since, I\xe2\x80\x99ve made it a rule to give the cheeriest greeting I can when I arrive at the office.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'Amid a growing focus on health and climate change, we are proud to have led the IPO for @beyondmeat, one of the fastest growing plant-based food companies in the US. Learn more via the link in our bio. #GSsustainability'

b'Meet @coachadaora, #10KWomen graduate and owner of @ez37solutions, a human resources and management consultancy based in Nigeria. As Adaora spoke to the business leaders in her community struggling through #COVID19, she understood how important leadership had suddenly become. Realizing the necessity, she began free coaching sessions for a number of organizations as a way of providing support to those who needed it most. Check out the link in our bio to learn more about Adaora, her business, and how to get involved in her coaching sessions.'
b'When curiosity leads, opportunities open. As a managing director in Warsaw, Jo Obstoj understands that true success stems from pursuing our interests. What passions motivate you?'

b'John Joyce, a managing director in our Hong Kong Global Markets Division, has been dedicating his leisure time to Seneca\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cLetters from a Stoic.\xe2\x80\x9d Speaking to why the book resonates with him, John explains, \xe2\x80\x9cThe Letters provide a fitting playbook of pragmatic minimalism for the challenges we all face today. Stripping the excess engenders autonomy, strength and gratitude\xe2\x80\xa6 all of which can come from the current crisis.\xe2\x80\x9d #WhatAreYouReading? :open_book:'

b'We helped issue a $150 million green bond for @theconservationfund, which will enable the protection of five million acres of working forests in the US. Read more via the link in our bio. #GSsustainability'

b'As the environment changes, small businesses have to adapt. For #10KSBUK grad Roni, that meant focusing on preparation. First, she signed up for Emergency Business Coaching to gain clarity on furloughs, #remoteworking, forecasting, and more. Now, Roni\xe2\x80\x99s working behind the scenes with leaders across the industry to identify new ways to help small businesses adapt and thrive. We\xe2\x80\x99re so proud to see one of our grads as a spokesperson for the #smallbiz community. #WorldEntrepreneursDay'

b'After being injured while cycling to work in July 2014, Rebecca, a Managing Director in Global Markets in #London, looked to #yoga as a way to recover and reset. Five years later, Rebecca has just published her first book, \xe2\x80\x9cThe Book of Yoga Self-Practice,\xe2\x80\x9d to support others in their own yoga journeys. #GSOutOfOffice
 
\xe2\x80\x9cAfter breaking my collarbone in the accident, my mobility was incredibly limited and I struggled with even the basic tasks months after. So I looked to yoga as a way to support my recovery. In my first class I proceeded to do a downward dog so badly the teacher had to come over and ask what was wrong with me. But I went back. Once, twice, and again. I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t touch my toes. I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t do a single chaturanga, even from my knees. But it was a start, and it felt like it was the start of something that might just stick.
 
Fast forward six years, yoga is now a fundamental part of my life. I wanted to write this book to share my experience, and provide some simple and effective tools anyone can leverage to help create and sustain a fulfilling and independent yoga practice.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'Chairman and CEO @davidsolomon shares one of the firm\xe2\x80\x99s main tenets with our 2020 interns\xe2\x80\x94bringing your whole self to work will always set you up for success. Visit the link in our bio to watch the conversation.'
